<SECTION 1> -- INTRODUCTION :

> * *SQL:* 
--Stands for Structured QUery Language. 
  It is a language for a database; companies like IBM have DB2, Oracle have MySQL, and Microsoft has SQL Server or MS Server. 
  It interacts with Relational Database Management System.
  It interacts with the database. 
  It is used to perform CRUD operations - Create, Read, Update, Delete.

> *Why SQL is important?* 
--SQL is widely popular and influential because of the following reasons :
          a> SQL allows the IT person to describe and access data in RDBMS.
          b> SQL allows you to work with other languages like Java, C, Python through SQL modules, libraries, and different connectors. 
          c> SQL lets you connect with additional tables and set permisiions, procedures, and views.

> *SEQUEL OR SQL?*
--SEQUEL invented by IBM. It stands for structured english query language. 
  Later, it was named as SQL.

*What is DATA?* 
--Collection of facts, numbers, words or anything related including pictures, video, images etc.

> *What is BASE?*
--It is like a system, hub, foundation or central location. 

> *What is DATABASE?*
--In simple words, it is a collection of data in a format that can be easily accessible.

> *What is DATABASE MANAGEMENT SYSTEM?* 
--A software application used to manage our Database is called as Database Management System.

> *How Database works?* 
--In simple words, user cannot directly access database, they use DBMS as a medium to connect to the database. Then, the database returns answers. We use SQL for DBMS to access Database.

> *Types of DATABASE ?*
--a> Relational Database  b>Non-Relational Database 
  a>Relational Database - Data stored in tables. 
                          We use SQL to work with relational DBMS. That is why we called this as Relational Database Management System (RDBMS).
                          Example - MySQL, ORACLE SQL SERVER, POSTGRES, MICROSOFT SQL SERVER 
  b>Non-Relational Database - Data not stored in tables. 
                              They can't understand SQL.
                              Example - MongoDB
